Hurricane Rosa threatens Phoenix, Las Vegas, Salt Lake City with flooding (areas with drought may benefit)
It’s rare for tropical low pressure to reach Arizona, but that’s exactly what’s likely to happen early next week as Hurricane Rosa’s remaining energy pulls across the desert in the southwestern United States, at the risk of sudden flooding.
The National Weather Service has already issued warnings of sudden flooding for Monday and Tuesday in western Arizona and into southern and eastern Nevada, southeastern California and Utah, including the cities of Phoenix, Flagstaff, Las Vegas and Salt Lake City.
Rosa is expected to travel directly across Phoenix on Tuesday, bringing rain late Monday.
The National Weather Service in Phoenix said in a tweet that only "ten tropical cyclones have maintained tropical storm or low pressure status within 200 miles of Phoenix since 1950!
Katrina (1967) was a hurricane within 40 miles (65 km) of the Arizona border".
The National Hurricane Center's latest models predict 5-10 cm of rain, with isolated amounts of up to 15 cm in the Mogollon Rim in Arizona.
Other parts of the desert in the southwestern United States, including the central Rocky Mountains and the Great Basin, are likely to receive 2.5-3 cm of rain with a risk of up to 10 cm.
In areas without the risk of sudden flooding, Rosa's rain can be a boon, as the region is affected by drought.
Flooding is very serious, but some of the rain will probably be beneficial because the southwestern United States is suffering from drought.
According to the U.S. Drought Monitor, just over 40 percent of Arizona suffers from at least extreme drought, the second-highest category, weather.com reported.
Hurricane Rosa will first travel across the Baja California Peninsula in Mexico.
Rosa, still with hurricane strength on Sunday morning with maximum wind strength of 135 km/h, is located 620 km south of Punta Eugenia in Mexico and travels north at 20 km/h.
The storm encounters cooler waters in the Pacific Ocean, which calms it down.
It is therefore expected to reach Mexico's landmass as a tropical storm on Monday afternoon or evening.
Parts of Mexico may receive heavy rain, which poses a significant risk of flooding.
"A total of 7.5-15 cm of rain is expected from Baja California to northwestern Sonora, with a risk of up to 25 cm," weather.com reported.
Rosa will then travel north across Mexico as a tropical storm and reach Arizona's border early Tuesday morning as a tropical low, which will then travel through Arizona and into southern Utah late Tuesday night.
"The biggest danger from Rosa and its residual energy is very heavy rain in Baja California, northwestern Sonora and the desert in the southwestern United States," the National Hurricane Center said.
The rain is expected to lead to life-threatening sudden floods and mud flows in the desert, as well as landslides in mountainous terrain.
