The comment comes after several parts of the U.S. government have made statements about AI, even though the U.S. does not have an overall formal AI strategy.
China presented its plan last year with the goal of becoming a leader in AI innovation by 2030.
"It would be a good start to double the budget for AI research, given that all other countries are so far behind the United States and we're looking for the next breakthrough in AI," Lee said.
A twice as large budget could double the chance of the next big AI breakthrough being made in the United States, Lee told CNBC in an interview earlier this week.
Lee, whose book "AI Superpowers: China, Silicon Valley and the New World Order" was published earlier this month by Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, is the CEO of Sinovation Ventures, which has invested in one of China's most prominent AI companies – Face++.
At Carnegie Mellon University in the 1980s, he worked on an AI system that beat the highest-ranking American Othello player, and later he was in charge of Microsoft Research and was CEO of Google's China department.
Lee previously mentioned technology competitions from the United States government, such as the Robot Challenge from the Advanced Research Projects Agency, and asked what the next one would be in order to identify future visionaries.
In the United States, researchers often have to work hard to get funding from the government, Lee said.
"It's not China that is taking the academic leaders away from us, but the companies," Lee said.
In recent years, Facebook, Google and other technology companies have hired leading personalities from universities to work on AI.
