Macedonia's referendum on name change
The people of Macedonia voted on Sunday in a referendum on whether the country's name should be changed to "Republic of North Macedonia", which would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that has hindered the country's attempts to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece has a province called Macedonia and claims that the name of its neighbour to the north constitutes a requirement on its territory and has therefore prevented Macedonia from joining NATO and the EU.
The two governments reached an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the name change would undermine the identity of Macedonia's Slavic majority.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has led to doubts as to whether the minimum 50 percent participation required for the referendum to be considered valid will be reached.
The question on the ballot in the referendum is as follows: "Are you in favour of membership of NATO and the EU with the approval of the agreement with Greece?"
But supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is worth changing the name if it allows Macedonia, one of the countries formed when Yugoslavia split, to join the EU and NATO.
"I am here to vote for the future of our country, for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because that means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgiyevska, 79, in Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough Members of Parliament have said that they intend to follow the result in order for it to be considered decisive.
The name change requires a two-thirds majority of parliament.
According to the State Electoral Commission, no irregularities had been reported at 1 p.m.
But participation was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary election in 2016 when 66 percent of registered voters voted.
"I vote for my children, we belong in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital Skopje.
Macedonia's Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko are voting in the referendum in Macedonia on the country's name change, which would open the way for membership of NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018.
Outside the Skopje parliament, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, organised a small stage and place out chairs in front of the tents set up by those boycotting the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to go with our heads in the air, not sneak in through the back door," Kavardarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they do not welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, like China and Russia, and become part of a Euro-Asian integration."
According to Prime Minister Zaev, membership of NATO would lead to much-needed investment in Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20 percent.
"I think the absolute majority will vote yes, because over 80% of our citizens are for the EU and NATO," Zaev said when he voted.
He said a "Yes" result would be a "confirmation of our future".
According to a survey published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute of Policy Investigation, between 30 and 43 percent of voters were going to vote in the referendum, which falls below the minimum participation required.
According to another survey conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57 percent of participants planned to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent of them would vote yes.
For the referendum to count, 50 percent of registered voters plus one vote are required.
If the referendum fails, it will be the first serious setback for Western-oriented government policy since it took over last May.
