John Edward: Language skills crucial for global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools maintain outstanding academic performance and this continued in 2018 with yet another set of outstanding test scores, only bolstered by individual and collective progress in sports, arts, music and other civic engagement.
With up to 30,000 students in Scotland, the schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible service for their students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further education, their chosen careers, and their role as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement custom curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and in demand subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
It’s a powerful reminder that we can’t just rely on English when we create relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year's test results show that languages are at the top of the list, with the highest number of approved results in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received A in the final exam Higher Grade.
Data, collected from SCIS 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students studying Mandarin received an A in Higher Grade, and 72 percent of those studying German, 69 percent of those studying French, and 63 percent of those studying Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as crucial skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language as a subject of choice is now considered as important as natural science, engineering, engineering and mathematics on curricula in independent schools and beyond.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that, for various reasons, employers found it difficult to fill their vacancies, with 17 percent attributed to a lack of language skills.
Having said that, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more future jobs requiring language skills, these skills are becoming necessary in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career choice, they will have a real advantage in the future if they have embraced a second language.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a survey of more than 4,000 adult Britons published by YouGov in 2013, 75 percent said they could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation in it, and where French was the only language that totaled in a two-digit percentage (15 percent).
That is why it is so important to invest in language teaching for our children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those used in developing countries, gives your child a better chance of finding meaningful employment in the future.
In Scotland, each school will teach different combinations of languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from within independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this area.
Scottish independent schools strive to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and get them with the skills necessary to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In a global economic environment, it is undoubtedly language that continues to be crucial for the country's future, so it must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland’s youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
