North Korea says it will "never" disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened their mistrust of the United States and it was not possible that the country would give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization's annual General Assembly that in the past year North Korea had taken "significant steps to show its benevolence", such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the facilities for nuclear tests and promising not to spread nuclear and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
"Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances there is no chance that we will unilaterally disarm ourselves first."
While Ri repeated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to an approach divided into stages for the nuclear power that would lead to North Korea being rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant, as it did not reject a unilateral nuclear solution entirely as Pyongyang had previously done.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work towards "denuclearization on the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the Korean War in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first dismantle its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also declined negotiations to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'decommissioning first' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its purpose through coercion, even objecting to the 'declaration to end the war'," Ri said.
"The notion that sanctions can get us on our knees is a pipe dream for the people who lack knowledge about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that U.S. leaders highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
The minister instead pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding, "If the party on this issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the Korean peninsula's nuclear disarmament would not have come to such a stalemate."
Yet the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's future ability to reach the U.S. mainland with rockets was inevitable after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take action for disarmament, but it said much work still remains and that sanctions must remain until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for this, saying that "whether it takes two years, three years or five months," doesn't matter.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the actions taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo, however, told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "the maintenance of Security Council sanctions must continue forcefully and without fail until we realize a complete, definitive, verified disarmament."
The Security Council has unanimously reinforced sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to stifle funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
