Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt "inferior" due to sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley says that feeling inferior to his peers during his upbringing because of his sexuality - but it also spurred him to be successful.
The 24-year-old said he didn't realize he wasn't like everyone else until he was in high school."
Speaking in the first Radio 4 Desert Island Discs presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he talked about gay rights to give others "hope".
He also said that he cared less about winning the Olympics after becoming a parent.
The popular show's regular host, Kirsty Young, has taken a few months off due to illness.
During his one-off appearance on Laverne's first program, Daley recounts how he felt "less worthy" than others during his upbringing, because "it wasn't socially acceptable to like boys and girls".
He said, "This feeling of feeling less worthy and feeling different has been a real source of the power and strength to succeed."
He wanted to prove that he was "someone," he said, so that he didn't betray everyone when they eventually found out about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medallist has become a high-profile advocate for LGBT rights and took advantage of his performance at this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to convince more countries to decriminalise homosexuality.
He said he took the floor because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without restrictions and wanted to give others "hope".
The three-time world champion said his crush on a man – American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 – “came as a surprise.”
Daley married the 20-year-old Oscar winner last year but he said the age difference had never been a problem.
"When you go through so much at such a young age" - he attended his first Olympics at 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he said it was hard to find someone of the same age with similar life experience.
The couple became parents in June to a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "whole life perspective" had changed.
