Germany's new warship delayed again
The German Navy's newest frigate would have been launched in 2014 to replace Cold War-era warships, but it won't be launched until at least next year due to faulty systems and high costs, local media reported.
Commissioning of the "Rhineland-Pfalz", the lead ship of the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg frigates, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper citing a military spokesman.
The ship should have joined the fleet already in 2014, but the problems that arose after the delivery were fatal to the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ordered by the fleet in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen frigates.
They will include a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth techniques, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to station the newest frigates for up to two years without contact with home ports.
But continuous delays mean that the pioneering warships – which allow Germany to project power abroad – are already obsolete when put into service, Die Zeit writes.
The fateful F125 frigate made headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to Blohm & Voss shipyards in Hamburg.
This was the first time that the Navy returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media indicated a number of important "software and hardware failures" that rendered the warship useless if used on a combat mission.
Weaknesses in the software were particularly important because ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors - only half of the crew of older frigates of the Bremen class.
It was also found that the ship has a significant excess weight, which leads to impaired performance and limits the Navy's ability to perform future upgrades.
The 7,000-ton "Rhineland-Pfalz" is believed to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Aside from faulty hardware, the entire project's price tag - including crew training - also becomes a problem.
It is said to have amounted to a staggering 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) - compared to 2.2 billion euros in the start-up phase.
Problems affecting the newest frigates become particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is declining.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, admitted that the fleet is actually "starting to lack fully equipped ships".
The official said that this is a growing problem, as old ships are being decommissioned but no replacement ships were provided.
He regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class could join the Navy.
The National Trust eavesdrops on the secret life of bats
New research carried out on a property in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape in their hunt for food.
We hope the results will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will follow southern and dwarf pipistrell as well as brown long-eared and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert audio analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat sounds and which species do what.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed area view of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain woodlands for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can aircraft and some chemical treatments of building materials as well as attacks from domestic cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technology to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, review nests, and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal area for them.
"Here at Threave we have a good area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of veteran trees and a variety of favorable habitats.
But there’s a lot about bats that’s still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us understand more about what they need to thrive.
He stresses the importance of searching for bats before performing maintenance within real estate, as it is possible that accidental destruction of a single nest could kill up to 400 females and young, and possibly wipe out an entire population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, bother or disturb them or destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer for the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species, we don't know how their populations are doing."
