Foreign buyers will be charged higher stamp duty when buying a property in the UK
Foreign buyers may pay higher stamp duty when buying property in the UK, and the extra money is used to help the homeless, according to the Tory party's new plans
Corbyn’s success in attracting young voters
The increase in stamp duty will apply to those who do not pay tax in the UK
The UK Treasury expects to raise up to 120 million pounds a year to help the homeless
Foreign buyers will have to pay a higher stamp duty when buying property in the UK. The extra money will be used to help the homeless, as will be announced by Prime Minister Theresa May today.
The measure will be seen as an attempt to neutralise Jeremy Corbyn’s success in attracting young voters with promises of more affordable housing and targeting high-income earners.
