Many affluent areas of the country, especially in the capital, have become ghost towns due to the high number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time abroad.
The new move comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a stamp tax cut to help more young people buy their first home.
He accused major construction companies of keeping prices up by buying up land without using it, and urged Theresa May to waive quotas on affordable housing to solve Britain's "deplorable housing situation."
